  "prompt": "What are the incarnations of lord Krishna in kaliyuga?",
  "response": "In Hinduism, Lord Krishna is considered an avatar of Lord Vishnu, and his life and teachings are recorded in ancient texts such as the Bhagavad Gita and the Mahabharata. In the context of the Yuga cycle, Krishna is primarily regarded as an avatar for the Dvapara Yuga rather than the Kali Yuga.\n\nIn the context of the Kali Yuga, some traditions within Hinduism believe that the Kalki Avatar will be the future and final incarnation of Lord Vishnu. Kalki is prophesied to appear at the end of the Kali Yuga to restore righteousness and dharma.\n\nHowever, within the scope of specific sects or spiritual traditions, other teachers or saints may be seen as incarnations of Krishna or possessing his qualities, but these beliefs can vary greatly among different followers and are not universally accepted as direct incarnations in the same manner as the ten principal avatars of Vishnu (the Dashavatara).\n\nIt is essential to understand that interpretations and beliefs about divine incarnations can vary widely within Hinduism, reflecting its vast diversity and richness in mythology and practice.",
